• UNION (`A | B`): The value can be an A OR a B. You can only safely use properties/methods that BOTH types share.
  ```typescript
  type StringOrNumber = string | number;
  // Only .toString() is available — it exists on both
  ```

• INTERSECTION (`A & B`): The value must be BOTH an A AND a B. It has ALL properties of both types.
  ```typescript
  type Admin = User & { permissions: string[] };
  // Admin has all User properties AND permissions
  ```

Intersections on primitives usually produce `never`:
  `type X = string & number; // never — nothing can be both string and number`

Intersections are commonly used for MIXINS, EXTENDING types without `&` and as an alternative to inheritance.

TypeScript has STRUCTURAL typing — if two types have the same shape, they are interchangeable. This can be dangerous:

```typescript
type UserId = string;
type PostId = string;

function getPost(id: PostId) { ... }
const userId: UserId = 'abc';
getPost(userId); // TypeScript allows this — both are string!
```

BRANDED TYPES add a nominal tag to prevent this:
```typescript
type UserId = string & { readonly __brand: 'UserId' };
type PostId = string & { readonly __brand: 'PostId' };

getPost(userId); // Error! UserId is not assignable to PostId
```

You typically create a factory function that casts:
```typescript
function makeUserId(s: string): UserId { return s as UserId; }
```

Used to prevent mixing up IDs, units (meters vs feet), currencies (USD vs EUR), validated vs unvalidated strings.

RECURSIVE TYPES reference themselves in their own definition — essential for tree structures, JSON, linked lists:

```typescript
// JSON value type
type JsonValue =
  | string | number | boolean | null
  | JsonValue[]
  | { [key: string]: JsonValue };

// Tree node
type TreeNode<T> = {
  value: T;
  children: TreeNode<T>[]; // recursive reference
};
```

Pre-TS 4.1 limitation: type ALIASES couldn't be immediately recursive in complex cases. The workaround was using interfaces (which could always be recursive). TS 4.1+ improved recursive conditional types.

TS 4.1 also enabled deeply recursive mapped types:
```typescript
type DeepReadonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: DeepReadonly<T[K]> };
```

KEY REMAPPING (`as` in mapped types, TS 4.1+) lets you control the OUTPUT key names:

```typescript
// Prefix every property key
type Prefixed<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as `get${Capitalize<string & K>}`]: () => T[K];
};

type User = { name: string; age: number };
type UserGetters = Prefixed<User>;
// { getName: () => string; getAge: () => number }
```

Filter keys by remapping to `never`:
```typescript
// Keep only string-valued properties
type StringProps<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as T[K] extends string ? K : never]: T[K];
};
```

Combined with template literal types, key remapping enables building event handler maps, getter/setter pairs, and form field types automatically from model types.

`NoInfer<T>` (introduced in TypeScript 5.4) tells TypeScript NOT to use a specific argument to infer the generic type — forcing it to be inferred from other arguments instead:

```typescript
function createState<T>(initial: T, callbacks: { onChange: (v: NoInfer<T>) => void }) {
  // ...
}

// Without NoInfer:
createState('idle', { onChange: v => {} });
// v could make T infer 'string' from onChange's parameter, causing conflicts

// With NoInfer:
// T is inferred from `initial` only ('idle' → literal 'idle')
// onChange MUST accept 'idle' — not some other string
```

Before TS 5.4, the workaround was `arg: T & {}` or using conditional types to block inference. `NoInfer` is much cleaner and explicit.
